                     <interp inst="t18440408-1245-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="simpleLarceny"></interp> for stealing three sheets, value 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; the goods of <persName id="t18440408-name-1178" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1178" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1178" type="surname" value="HAMMOND"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1178" type="given" value="MARK"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18440408-1245-offence-1 t18440408-name-1178"></join>Mark Hammond</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440408-name-1179" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1179" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1179" type="surname" value="HAMMOND"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1179" type="given" value="HANNAH"></interp>HANNAH HAMMOND</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of Mark Hammond, and live in Chapman-street, Commercial-road, East. The prisoner lodged at my house for three weeks and three days—he occupied a furnished room, with his wife and two children—he left on the 23rd of March—I missed three sheets and a table-cloth from the room—I afterwards saw the prisoner—I charged him with having taken them—he said he had taken them and pledged them, and said I should have them returned—I said, "It is impossible I can take your word, I have waited nine days, in consequence of a note you sent me"—he did not let me know where he had gone to—these are the sheets.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> On the Saturday before I left, did you not tell me if I was in want of money, I might pledge one of these articles? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Certainly not—you did not say if I would lend you 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. till the following day, you would not part with them—I did not send word if you wanted a loaf of bread you might have it—I found this note down by the door, on the evening they sent me the key—they did not send me any address—<hi rend="italic">note read</hi>—"Mrs. Ham<lb></lb>mond, I am sorry to leave you, but as it was your wish for us to do so, we have done so. I am again disappointed in receiving my money, and shall not have it till April. Your sheets and table-cover are at wash; and on Monday evening you shall have them. I will send you the rent with them."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440408-name-1180" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1180" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1180" type="surname" value="STARR"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1180" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM STARR</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman.</hi>) I went with Mrs. Hammond to No. 13, Baker's-row, and found the prisoner—she gave him in charge—I asked where the sheets were—he said they were in the wash, and then be told me they were in pledge—I received some duplicates from his wife.</p>
               <p>
